tribution.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Unit -> Integration proof: the failure occurs at a concrete module handoff between independent reviewer outputs and the merge component (schema/identity/attribution mapping), not inside one pure function alone. Integration-brake checks: no real OS/network/subprocess is required for this behavior, so no System escalation; correctness does not depend on AI output quality if reviewer outputs are supplied as fixtures, so no Agentic escalation; this behavior tests one merge operation, not multi-step agentic chaining, so no Workflow escalation. Rejected higher levels based on behavior text: it specifies merge conflict preservation/attribution logic, which is deterministic once inputs are given.","test_description":"Wire real reviewer-output DTOs (or serializers) from two modules into the actual merge module using fixture outputs that intentionally conflict on the same clause ID. Assert unified report retains both assessments and correct reviewer attribution without overwriting/dedup loss.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full pipeline — dispatching to all three reviewers, collecting results, merging into a unified report — completes correctly for a real contract without losing any individual reviewer's findings.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"Unit is insufficient because this behavior is explicitly end-to-end orchestration across dispatcher, three reviewer clients, collector, and merger (multiple interface handoffs). Integration is insufficient because pipeline correctness under parallel reviewer execution requires exercising real external call behavior (latency/ordering/failures), which crosses into System. System is still insufficient because reviewers are AI and correctness of \"real contract\" findings depends on actual model-produced outputs fr